Business Problem¶

The Centers for Disease Control & Prevention (CDC) seek to strengthen public health surveillance & lower the incident of diabetes through data-driven decision-making. Diabetes is an escalating public health emergency that leads to serious complications like cardiovascular disorder, kidney failure, & amputations. The primary issue is to foresee a persons risk of developing diabetes based on lifestyle behaviours, medical history & demographic characteristics.

Importance¶

>For public health agencies (CDC) enables evidence–based policymaking & resource allocation to populations at risk
>For healthcare providers facilities timely intervention & personalized therapeutic strategies.
>Insurance & Employers assists in health risk appraisal, lowering medical expenses & implementing wellness initiatives.

Data collection strategy¶

>Using Available Datasets: Utilize CDC’s publicly accessible dataset of diabetes health indicators for analysis.
>Supplementary Data sources: Incorporate electronic health records, surveys & wearable device data to provide depth.

https://www.cdc.gov/brfss/
https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/abdelazizsami/cdc-diabetes-health-indicators/data

Defining the problem as a Machine learning exercise¶

This is a supervised classification problem, attempting to predict how probable a person will develop diabetes based on historical health data.¶

>Data Preprocessing.
>EDA (Exploratory Data Analysis).
>Feature Engineering.
>Model selection & Training.
>Model Evaluation.
>Saving the model.

  • 0 = no
  • 1 = yes

NoDocbcCost (Was there a time in the past 12 months when you needed to see a doctor but could not because of cost?)

  • 0 = no

  • 1 = excellent
  • 2 = very good
  • 3 = good
  • 4 = fair
  • 5 = poor

MentHlth

  • Now thinking about your mental health, which includes stress, depression, and problems with emotions, for how many days during the past 30 days was your mental health not good? scale 1-30 days

PhysHlth

  • Now thinking about your physical health, which includes physical illness and injury, for how many days during the past 30 days was your physical health not good? scale 1-30 days

DiffWalk (Do you have serious difficulty walking or climbing stairs?)

  • 0 = no
  • 1 = yes

Sex

  • 0 = female
  • 1 = male

Age (13-level age category)

  • 13 = 80 or older

Education (Education level (EDUCA see codebook) scale 1-6)

  • 1 = Never attended school or only kindergarten

  • 3 = Grades 9 through 11 (Some high school)
  • 4 = Grade 12 or GED (High school graduate)
  • 5 = College 1 year to 3 years (Some college or technical school)
  • 6 = College 4 years or more (College graduate)

Income (Income scale 1-8)

  • 1 = less than 10,000
  • 5 = less than 35,000
  • 8 = 75,000 or more

Observations

  • From Correlation between GenHlth & DiffWalk is 0.46. It explain that, with improper health condition may cause difficult in walking.
  • From Correlation between GenHlth & PhysHlth is 0.52. So, Physical health maintaince is most important for good general health.
  • With mutual correlation we can say that worse PhysHlth leads DiffHlth, and correlation between them is 0.48
  • HighBP vs Age correlation is 0.34. Higher the age Higher the BP
  • Correlation between MenHlth and PhsyHlth is 0.35, worsening mental health may correlate with physical health problems.
  • Education vs GenHlth is -0.28. Higher education levels may correlate with self reported general health.
  • Correlation between Income and GenHlth, PhsyHlth, DiffWalk is negative. Highlights that higher income encorperates better access to medical and physical activity facilities.
  • Age correlates positively with High Blood Pressure(0.34), Stroke(0.13), and Difficulty in Walking(0.2), align with common aging trends in health.

Conclusion¶

>This proposed machine learning pipeline effectively predicts diabetes risk from lifestyle, medical history, and demographic data. By leveraging multiple models and feature importance details, it provides a data-driven approach to a pressing public health issue.
>Even though the solution has good predictive power, data imbalance, explainability, and generalization issues must be addressed for the best outcome. Employing SHAP values, cutting-edge resampling techniques, and regular model updating can boost reliability even further.
>From a business perspective, these findings justify evidence-based policymaking, early detection of disease, cost-saving interventions, and targeted community health interventions. Maximum real-world usefulness can be attained by applying this model in healthcare software or public health dashboards.
>Proactive diabetes prevention and management can be the outcome of this solution with ongoing refinement and integration with healthcare systems.

Strengths¶

    >Data-Driven Strategy Uses actual CDC real-world data, providing credibility.
    >Comparisons of many ML models Decision Tree, Random Forest, and Gradient Boosting provide comparison and best model selection.
    >Cross-Validation & Hyperparameter Tuning Enhances model generalizability and prevents overfitting.
    >Comprehensive Evaluation Metrics Employs ROC-AUC and confusion matrix for a balanced assessment.
    >Feature Scaling Used Ensures model performance and stability improvement.

Limitations & Challenges¶

>Feature Engineering Scope The data set can be supplemented with external health records, measured wearable data, etc.
>Imbalanced Data Handling Where diabetes cases are under sampled, resampling techniques (SMOTE) can improve prediction.
>Complexity of Complex Model Explainability Random Forest and Gradient Boosting are harder to interpret than Decision Trees.Data Quality and            >Missing Values :Missing or inaccurate data can impact model performance; robust imputation techniques or alternative data sources may be necessary.
>Applying to Various Groups The model might not generalize effectively to varied populations or unseen populations, necessitating retraining from time to time using new datasets.

Business Implications of the Findings¶

>Public Health Agencies Assists in evidence-based policy-making and focused interventions.
>Healthcare Providers Facilitates early detection and personalized treatment plans.
>For Employers & Insurers Helps in health risk assessment and cost-saving measures.
>Pharmaceutical & Medical Research Facilitates drug development and preventive care efforts by defining high-risk groups and their most critical health indicators.
>Community Health Programs Coordinates special wellness initiatives to promote physical activity and healthy eating habits among at-risk populations.

Data-Driven Recommendations¶

>Feature Importance Insights Wherever possible, utilize SHAP or tree-based model feature importance to choose top predictors.
>Enhancing Model Performance Try more sophisticated methods such as XGBoost or deep learning.
>Deployment Strategy Think about incorporating the model into healthcare software or public health dashboards.
>Handling Class Imbalance If the data is imbalanced (e.g., diabetic cases are fewer), try using techniques such as SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique) or weighted loss functions to enhance model performance.
>Real-Time Monitoring & Continuous Learning Implement a feedback cycle where the model is continuously revised with new data to learn from emerging health trends and improve prediction accuracy over time.

Most informative Features of the model¶

>Age: A highly significant predictor, as the risk of diabetes increases with age.
>BMI (Body Mass Index): A high BMI is strongly related to an increased risk of diabetes.
>Physical Activity: Exercise on a regular basis lowers the risk of diabetes.
>Blood Pressure Levels High blood pressure is usually associated with diabetes and other bodily issues.
>Smoking Status:  Smoking can increase insulin resistance and result in diabetes risk.
>Consuming Alcohol: Consuming excess alcohol can lead to weight gain and metabolic issues, increasing the risk of diabetes.
